WEBVTT

1
00:00:29.418 --> 00:00:30.799
DAVID: My name is Dave Paulides

2
00:00:30.833 --> 00:00:32.559
and I'm a former
police detective


3
00:00:32.594 --> 00:00:33.974
and current
investigative author


4
00:00:34.009 --> 00:00:36.943
focused primarily
on mysterious disappearances


5
00:00:36.977 --> 00:00:38.772
in the North American
wilderness.


6
00:00:43.294 --> 00:00:45.124
MAN: [SHOUTING] Melvin!

7
00:00:45.158 --> 00:00:48.541
DAVID: My journey into the disappearances began
when I was visiting a national park

8
00:00:48.575 --> 00:00:52.372
and was approached
by two park rangers
who knew I was an author.


9
00:00:52.407 --> 00:00:57.412
They described strange
circumstances over the years
involving missing hikers.


10
00:00:57.446 --> 00:01:00.415
I immediately began looking
into the phenomenon.


11
00:01:00.449 --> 00:01:02.072
Eight years
and eight books later,


12
00:01:02.106 --> 00:01:05.247
I've now researched 1200
cases that fit the profile

13
00:01:05.282 --> 00:01:08.078
we are about to examine.

14
00:01:08.112 --> 00:01:11.598
While these cases involve
people of all ages and
all walks of life,


15
00:01:11.633 --> 00:01:14.291
I've chosen to present some
of the most intriguing cases


16
00:01:14.325 --> 00:01:15.982
involving hunters.

17
00:01:16.016 --> 00:01:19.399
Generally speaking,
hunters are very experienced,


18
00:01:19.434 --> 00:01:22.471
aware, and knowledgeable
outdoorsmen.


19
00:01:23.300 --> 00:01:25.785
And so, when one vanishes,

20
00:01:25.819 --> 00:01:27.959
you know something unusual
has occurred.


21
00:01:41.973 --> 00:01:44.424
One of the most perplexing
cases I've examined


22
00:01:44.459 --> 00:01:47.186
involves a hunter named
Thomas Messick,


23
00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:51.500
who in 2015, went missing
in North-East New York.


24
00:01:58.576 --> 00:01:59.819
DAVID: For people
who don't know,


25
00:01:59.853 --> 00:02:03.305
the FBI doesn't investigate
missing adults.


26
00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:07.689
There's a sub-category
for the FBI, that they can
become involved


27
00:02:07.723 --> 00:02:10.174
in the disappearance
of extremely young children


28
00:02:10.209 --> 00:02:11.900
under a certain set of criteria.

29
00:02:13.488 --> 00:02:17.147
So, the million dollar
question is, why would
the FBI arrive


30
00:02:17.181 --> 00:02:18.734
on Tom Messick's case?

31
00:02:37.684 --> 00:02:41.654
WIFE: He loved the outdoors.
He loved being in the woods.


32
00:02:41.688 --> 00:02:43.966
Hunting and fishing
was his life.


33
00:02:51.526 --> 00:02:52.906
You want a cookie, honey?

34
00:02:57.463 --> 00:03:00.949
BEVERLY: He was
a very good husband,
very good father.


35
00:03:02.364 --> 00:03:05.574
And I don't think
you will find anybody


36
00:03:06.437 --> 00:03:08.715
who ever met him
who didn't like him.


37
00:03:09.889 --> 00:03:11.546
DAVID: And how many kids
did you guys have?


38
00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:13.410
BEVERLY: We had three sons.

39
00:03:13.444 --> 00:03:15.757
Tommy, Jean, and Rob.

40
00:03:17.586 --> 00:03:20.244
So, tell me about your dad.
What kind of guy was he?


41
00:03:20.279 --> 00:03:25.145
He was kinda, "Do what you got
to go to get things done."


42
00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:28.218
Never had a contractor
in the house.
We always did everything.


43
00:03:28.252 --> 00:03:29.564
You name it.

44
00:03:29.598 --> 00:03:31.980
We lifted the house up,
put a foundation under it.


45
00:03:32.014 --> 00:03:33.706
When I was digging it out,
I looked up at him,


46
00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:35.155
he had a cup of coffee
in his hand


47
00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:36.605
and I said,
"Why don't we get a backhoe?"


48
00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:38.262
And he said,
"I have one, right there."


49
00:03:38.297 --> 00:03:40.057
[BOTH LAUGH]

50
00:03:40.091 --> 00:03:42.439
What did you guys like to do
as a family?


51
00:03:42.473 --> 00:03:45.890
We camped.
We did a lot of camping.


52
00:03:45.925 --> 00:03:48.893
And the boys loved it
and, you know,


53
00:03:48.928 --> 00:03:52.242
I was kind of the outsider
because they were boys


54
00:03:52.276 --> 00:03:56.176
and they hunted and fished
and did those things.


55
00:03:58.524 --> 00:04:01.734
SID: I knew Tom
before we earned enough


56
00:04:01.768 --> 00:04:03.839
'cause he used
to work in Norton with me.


57
00:04:05.185 --> 00:04:08.982
I knew him probably
about 55 years
or somewhere around there.


58
00:04:09.017 --> 00:04:10.777
DAVID: What did you guys like
to do together?


59
00:04:12.227 --> 00:04:13.677
Hunt. Hunt and fish.

60
00:04:13.711 --> 00:04:15.644
It's what we did
all the time, really.


61
00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:18.958
[SID'S WIFE SPEAKING]

62
00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:21.961
Yeah, we both had trailers

63
00:04:21.995 --> 00:04:26.137
in which we used
to go trailing all the time,
come to think of it.


64
00:04:26.172 --> 00:04:28.278
We all got
the same vacation in Norton,


65
00:04:28.312 --> 00:04:33.938
so we all took off and went
to different places like that.


66
00:04:33.973 --> 00:04:37.287
So, what was your introduction
to the outdoors?


67
00:04:37.321 --> 00:04:41.877
It was always there
because my father
always hunted and fished.


68
00:04:41.912 --> 00:04:46.606
ROB: We got a camp up North,
not far from Brant Lake,


69
00:04:46.641 --> 00:04:48.815
for about a week every year.

70
00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:50.817
A bunch of guys get together
and go hunting.


71
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.899
BEVERLY: He taught
hunter training
for a long time.


72
00:05:03.934 --> 00:05:08.318
He probably taught every one
of the kids around here.


73
00:05:08.352 --> 00:05:12.011
SID: Tom was a great guy. 
He was an old airborne Ranger.

74
00:05:12.045 --> 00:05:14.841
He was unbelievable
in the woods.


75
00:05:14.876 --> 00:05:17.672
He taught my hunting class for
me to get my hunting license.


76
00:05:17.706 --> 00:05:19.259
He taught survival.

77
00:05:19.294 --> 00:05:21.814
BEVERLY: He had gunpowder
blow up in his face,


78
00:05:21.848 --> 00:05:23.022
and that's how he lost...

79
00:05:23.056 --> 00:05:26.750
He had a 159 stitches
in his hand


80
00:05:26.784 --> 00:05:28.855
and he lost his eye that way.

81
00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:30.719
So, he would say to these kids,

82
00:05:30.754 --> 00:05:33.239
"This is what happens
if you're not careful."


83
00:05:33.273 --> 00:05:35.206
I mean, he had a lot of issues
over the years,


84
00:05:35.241 --> 00:05:39.038
but it never really seemed
to slow him down or anything.


85
00:05:39.797 --> 00:05:42.041
So, obviously, he had one eye.

86
00:05:42.075 --> 00:05:43.180
Yeah.

87
00:05:43.214 --> 00:05:45.078
He was sort of blind,
it wasn't really that great,


88
00:05:45.113 --> 00:05:46.942
but he could actually see
out of it.


89
00:05:46.977 --> 00:05:48.530
And hearing was an issue?

90
00:05:48.565 --> 00:05:49.773
He wasn't
that great with hearing.


91
00:05:49.807 --> 00:05:51.947
Hearing,
he needed hearing aids.


92
00:05:51.982 --> 00:05:55.192
Would Tom be the kind of guy
who would drink a lot or...


93
00:05:55.226 --> 00:05:58.678
No. He didn't drink
that much, no.


94
00:05:58.713 --> 00:06:01.992
So, the day when you guys went
hunting, did you guys drink
when you hunt?


95
00:06:02.544 --> 00:06:04.304
No.

96
00:06:04.339 --> 00:06:07.411
We might have beer
with us in the truck.


97
00:06:07.446 --> 00:06:11.760
Out in the woods, we might have
a beer or something like that.


98
00:06:11.795 --> 00:06:14.314
Nothing excessive, you know?

99
00:06:14.349 --> 00:06:17.317
How would you describe
your dad's judgment?


100
00:06:18.146 --> 00:06:19.941
It was good.

101
00:06:19.975 --> 00:06:23.807
ROB: In fact, it was
probably one of his better days

102
00:06:23.841 --> 00:06:24.946
I had seen in a long time.

103
00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:28.467
He was in good spirits
and moving great.


104
00:06:28.501 --> 00:06:32.263
Didn't seem to even have
an ache or pain
in him that day.


105
00:06:32.298 --> 00:06:33.368
He was moving good.

106
00:06:42.273 --> 00:06:43.827
DAVID: How often
do you think about it?


107
00:06:44.862 --> 00:06:46.933
I just think about it, well...

108
00:06:46.968 --> 00:06:50.109
SID: You know, it
always pops into your mind.

109
00:06:54.493 --> 00:06:56.426
We were doing
just kind of a quick thing.


110
00:06:57.496 --> 00:06:59.118
It was late actually.

111
